---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
const reviewed = "June 2026";
---
<Base
  title="Company Formation & Tax in the Czech Republic 2026: s.r.o. & Corporate Tax | ARM Management"
  description="A current guide to setting up a company in the Czech Republic — the s.r.o., the 21% corporate tax, 21% VAT, and registration via the Commercial Register, with official sources."
>
  <main>
    <section class="page-hero">
      <div class="page-hero__bg" style="background-image:url('/images/ed-zurich.jpg')"></div>
      <div class="page-hero__overlay"></div>
      <div class="page-hero__content container">
        <span class="eyebrow">Guide · Czech Republic</span>
        <h1>Company Formation &amp; Tax in the Czech Republic</h1>
        <p>A stable, central CEE base — the s.r.o., a flat corporate tax, VAT, and a predictable, EU-aligned compliance framework.</p>
        <div class="btn-row" style="justify-content:flex-start;margin-top:30px">
          <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Speak With a Senior Advisor →</a>
          <a href="/services/company-formation" class="btn-secondary">Company Formation Services</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section section--warm">
      <div class="container--narrow">
        <div class="guide-meta reveal">
          <span><strong>Last reviewed:</strong> {reviewed}</span>
          <span><strong>Primary source:</strong>
            <a href="https://www.financnisprava.cz/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Financial Administration</a>
          </span>
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
          <p class="reveal lede">The Czech Republic offers a central European location, a transparent legal system and full foreign ownership rights. Its tax framework is stable and easy to model — a single corporate rate and a simplified two-rate VAT system after the 2024 consolidation.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Choosing an entity</h2>
          <p class="reveal">The standard vehicle is the <strong>s.r.o.</strong> (společnost s ručením omezeným, private limited company), which can be formed with nominal capital (the statutory minimum is CZK 1, though more is usual in practice). Larger businesses use the <strong>a.s.</strong> (akciová společnost, joint-stock). Registration is via the Commercial Register, followed by corporate-tax registration with the Financial Administration, which issues the tax identification number (DIČ).</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Corporate tax and VAT</h2>
          <div class="rate-table reveal">
            <table>
              <thead><tr><th>Tax</th><th>Rate</th></tr></thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Corporate income tax</td><td>21%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>VAT (DPH, standard)</td><td>21%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>VAT (reduced)</td><td>12% (books 0%)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>VAT registration threshold</td><td>CZK 2,000,000 (~€80,000)</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p class="reveal">Corporate income tax is <strong>21%</strong> (raised from 19% for periods beginning in 2024) and applies to all business profits, including most capital gains. VAT (DPH) is <strong>21%</strong> standard with a single <strong>12%</strong> reduced rate (the previous 15% and 10% rates were merged in 2024) and zero-rating on books. VAT registration is mandatory once turnover exceeds CZK 2,000,000 over twelve months. Large multinational groups are within scope of the OECD Pillar Two minimum-tax rules.</p>

          <div class="callout reveal">
            <strong>Stable and straightforward.</strong> With one corporate rate and a simplified VAT structure, Czechia is easy to model for long-term operations and buy-and-build strategies across Central Europe. The participation exemption can shelter qualifying dividends and share-sale gains.
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Frequently asked questions</h2>
          <div class="reveal">
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>What is the corporate tax rate in the Czech Republic?</h4><p>21% (raised from 19% for periods beginning in 2024).</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>How much capital do I need for an s.r.o.?</h4><p>The statutory minimum is CZK 1, though a more substantial amount is usual in practice.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>What is the Czech VAT rate?</h4><p>21% standard with a single 12% reduced rate; registration applies above CZK 2,000,000 turnover.</p></div>
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Official sources</h2>
          <ul class="sources reveal">
            <li><a href="https://www.financnisprava.cz/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Financial Administration of the Czech Republic</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://or.justice.cz/ias/ui/rejstrik" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Commercial Register (justice.cz)</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.czechinvest.org/en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CzechInvest</a></li>
          </ul>

          <p class="reveal disclaimer">This guide is general information prepared by ARM Management and is current as at {reviewed}. It is not legal or tax advice; rules and thresholds change. Confirm against the Financial Administration, or with an advisor, before acting.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="cta-section guide-cta">
      <span class="eyebrow is-center reveal" style="justify-content:center">Speak With ARM</span>
      <h2 class="reveal">Set up in the Czech Republic with confidence.</h2>
      <p class="reveal">ARM Management advises international companies on Czech entity formation, registration and tax compliance, alongside wider CEE structuring. Begin with a confidential conversation.</p>
      <div class="btn-row reveal">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Schedule a Consultation →</a>
        <a href="/services/company-formation" class="btn-secondary">Company Formation Services</a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"Article","headline":"Company Formation & Tax in the Czech Republic 2026","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"ARM Management"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"ARM Management"},"dateModified":"2026-06-01","mainEntityOfPage":"https://arm-management.com/insights/czech-republic-company-formation"})} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the corporate tax rate in the Czech Republic?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"21% (raised from 19% for periods beginning in 2024)."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How much capital do I need for a Czech s.r.o.?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The statutory minimum is CZK 1, though a more substantial amount is usual in practice."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the Czech VAT rate?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"21% standard with a single 12% reduced rate; registration applies above CZK 2,000,000 turnover."}}]})} />
</Base>
